    import bpy

class OBJECT_OT_AddBezierCurve(bpy.types.Operator):
    bl_idname = "object.add_bezier_curve"
    bl_label = "Add Bezier Curve"
    # We include REGISTER so it shows in the "Adjust Last Operation" panel
    # and UNDO if you want to make the operation undoable:
    bl_options = {'REGISTER', 'UNDO'}

    z_value: bpy.props.FloatProperty(
        name="Z Value",
        description="Adjustable Z parameter for the curve handles",
        default=1.9,
        min=-10.0,
        max=10.0
    )

    # Blender will display the operator properties in the "Last Operation" panel.
    def execute(self, context):
        curve_data = bpy.data.curves.new('BezierCurve', type='CURVE')
        curve_data.dimensions = '3D'

        spline = curve_data.splines.new('BEZIER')
        spline.bezier_points.add(1)

        spline.bezier_points[0].co = (0, 0, 0)
        spline.bezier_points[1].co = (0, 2, 0)

        z = self.z_value

        spline.bezier_points[0].handle_left_type = 'FREE'
        spline.bezier_points[0].handle_right_type = 'FREE'
        spline.bezier_points[0].handle_left = (0, 0, 0)
        spline.bezier_points[0].handle_right = (0, 1, z)

        spline.bezier_points[1].handle_left_type = 'FREE'
        spline.bezier_points[1].handle_right_type = 'FREE'
        spline.bezier_points[1].handle_left = (0, 1, z)
        spline.bezier_points[1].handle_right = (0, 1, 0)

        curve_obj = bpy.data.objects.new('BezierCurveObject', curve_data)
        context.collection.objects.link(curve_obj)

        context.view_layer.objects.active = curve_obj
        curve_obj.select_set(True)

        return {'FINISHED'}

def menu_func(self, context):
    self.layout.operator(OBJECT_OT_AddBezierCurve.bl_idname, text="Add Bezier Curve")

def register():
    bpy.utils.register_class(OBJECT_OT_AddBezierCurve)
    bpy.types.VIEW3D_MT_object.prepend(menu_func)

def unregister():
    bpy.utils.unregister_class(OBJECT_OT_AddBezierCurve)
    bpy.types.VIEW3D_MT_object.remove(menu_func)

if __name__ == "__main__":
    register()

    import bpy

# Create a new curve object
curve_data = bpy.data.curves.new('BezierCurve', type='CURVE')
curve_data.dimensions = '3D'

# Create a new spline
spline = curve_data.splines.new('BEZIER')
spline.bezier_points.add(1)  # Total two points

# Set the first point and handles
spline.bezier_points[0].co = (0, 0, 0)


z = 1.9

# Set the second point and handles
spline.bezier_points[1].co = (0, 2, 0)

spline.bezier_points[0].handle_left_type = 'FREE'
spline.bezier_points[0].handle_right_type = 'FREE'
spline.bezier_points[0].handle_left = (0, 0, 0)
spline.bezier_points[0].handle_right = (0, 1, z)


spline.bezier_points[1].handle_left_type = 'FREE'
spline.bezier_points[1].handle_right_type = 'FREE'
spline.bezier_points[1].handle_left = (0, 1, z)
spline.bezier_points[1].handle_right = (0, 1, 0)

# Create an object and link it to the scene
curve_obj = bpy.data.objects.new('BezierCurveObject', curve_data)
bpy.context.collection.objects.link(curve_obj)

# Select the created object
bpy.context.view_layer.objects.active = curve_obj
curve_obj.select_set(True)
